insta_description:
This simultaneously feels like yesterday and 1000 years ago. ‚Å†
‚Å†
I‚Äôd like to keep the doom and gloom to a minimum, and you won‚Äôt be seeing posts for the next 30 days about all the madness happening out there in the world because I don‚Äôt think it helps anything.  Awareness, yes.  Wallowing and panic, definitely no.‚Å†
‚Å†
There‚Äôs a lot of industry leaders out there pushing the message that everything is totally fine - or even more mind blowing - that nothing has actually changed.  I disagree.‚Å†
‚Å†
Being in an events industry, our paychecks are dependent on (wait for it)...events.  This is uncharted territory.  There are small businesses - myself included - who were counting on balances being paid to cover rent and mortgages and groceries and healthcare.  When those events are postponed, those balances disappear.  The bills don‚Äôt.‚Å†
‚Å†
I have the most amazing couples and clients who have been so understanding and so flexible with payment plans and new schedules.  If you‚Äôre having to postpone your event, please be gentle with your vendors.  This is just as devastating and scary for them as it is for you.  Let‚Äôs all extend a little grace so we can get through this together.‚Å†

Looking forward to sunnier skies ahead.‚Å†üíï

Our hearts go out to everyone that has been impacted by the Corona virus (COVID-19). S3 Coffee Bar is concerned about your health, the health of our staff and community. 
The COVID 19 virus has not only impacted us, but also several local small businesses. We hope that with your continued support we can remain open and continue to serve you the drinks and food you've come to love.

We thank you for your patience and support as we try to navigate through these challenging circumstances. For us, it would still be an honor to serve you coffee and other wonderful drinks to get you through your day. 
As of now, we are still allowed to serve you food and drinks, but only as pick up "to-go" orders. For now our store will remain open with limited hours from 8:00am to 4:00pm for you to pick up your order. Soon we also hope to open our drive-thru for your added convenience. Please keep an eye-out on our social media platforms for the latest news. 
Additionally, another way you can support is by picking up one of our gift cards, which you can order from the link in our bio. You can use these for yourself or to give to your friends and family as gifts.

Again thanks for you patience and we will let you know once things settle down and things get back to normally, but until then please stay safe along with your loved ones.

Love,

Rating: 4/5 ‚≠êÔ∏è It‚Äôs been pretty cold and rainy the past couple of days here in the #BayArea so you know we had to cozy up with a bowl of #ramen! We visited Orenchi Ramen in #RedwoodCity to see how they stack up against our favorite ramen spots in the Bay! We ordered the Orenchi Ramen Tonkotsu, the Cha-shu Gohan, and the Chicken Karaage! insta_description:
Using purely the bus & subway in LA to get around requires you to think on your feet. Often the trip that you have meticulously planned out the night before can go haywire in the morning & if it changes midway, it can set off mild panic buttons as the next bus might be 30mins - 1hr away. As long as the 1st bus is tried & true, generally the next course of action can be determined.
So, it is good to have alternatives at the beginning cuz no doubt one of the connections will be late or sometimes early, which can also leave you in the lurch. And I try to find a route that has minimal transfers as, according to the Murphy's Law adage, "Anything that can go wrong will go wrong". Less chances for this, the better.

But I've got to admit I feel a bit like Forrest Gump (the one without the virusÔºÅ) when it doesn't work out as I walk or run for miles to get to the next alternative.

If you listen to most people here, "you need a car" but, so far, so good. It has stood me in good stead & I quite enjoy tackling that beast on a daily basis, even if it isn't such a timely option.

accessibility_caption: Photo by Fit | Mind Body Spirit in Menlo Park, California with @noellejohnson, @justindavidcarl, @carlylynwise, and @relatedgarments. Image may contain: 1 person, sitting and indoor
insta_description:
‚ÄúEvery adversity has the seed of an equivalent or greater benefit.‚Äù -Napoleon Hill

Now more than ever we need to cultivate a mindset of dynamic flexibility, lead with compassion, choose happiness, choose faith, take 100% responsibility, be a lighthouse for others & always find the golden gift hidden within every challenge.

There is a lot of fear in the world & that‚Äôs totally understandable. We are in uncertain times & many are suffering.

Instead of running from the fear or pretending that it doesn‚Äôt exist let‚Äôs acknowledge it, take responsibility (the ability to respond) & take positive action.

Fear is the mind's ways of signaling to us that we should prepare. So let us take the actions to prepare in a responsible manner that empowers us to work together as ONE BIG COMMUNITY to solve the current challenge. ‚ÄúSocial distancing‚Äù is one way for us to work together. This will lessen the speed at which the disease can spread, allowing our healthcare system to appropriately deal with the health challenge without getting overloaded.

So while large public gatherings are not ideal this is NOT AN EXCUSE TO DISCONNECT. Fear loves disconnection.

Instead let us use this challenge as an opportunity to love more, love deeper & use the gift of technology to stay connected.

Really this is an incredible opportunity for us to CONNECT AT A DEEPER LEVEL. We can do this in-person with those we live with/near and virtually with those we don‚Äôt.

I feel so lucky & blessed that I get to connect even more deeply with my two powerful felines at home!

Plus, I plan to continue to get outside alone & in small groups, exercise outdoors & at home, eat healthfully, sleep, meditate, pray, make magic, read, build skills & double down on my health in all ways -- mentally, physically, emotionally & spiritually!

Lastly, I plan to continuously practice being dynamically flexible with the changing circumstances while always choosing happiness, choosing faith, & choosing to be grateful for all the abundance in my life!

Energy flows wherever focus goes. Every day is a great day to choose faith over fear, love more, be healthy, find the hidden gifts & live a magical life!
.
.

insta_description:
Have you ever wondered how clearcutting effects wildlife? The American Marten, California Spotted Owl, and the Northern Flying Squirrel are just three of MANY wildlife creatures that are harmed by clearcutting. .
‚ÄúOne of the the worst consequences of removing all or nearly all vegetation in a clearcut is the loss of essential food and shelter for wildlife, and the creation of fragmented patches of forest habitat across the landscape. As intact forests are fragmented, edges are created, opening canopy and exposing certain species to more competition, predation and parasitism. Loss of habitat and habitat fragmentation are among the leading factors contributing to the decline of many wildlife species. Clearcuts also remove forest structural elements common in mature, diverse forests that are critical for wildlife, such as large, older trees; dead, standing snags; and rotting logs and woody debris.‚Äù For more information, go to: http://www.stopclearcuttingca.org/resources/clearcutting-and-wildlife/

Do your research properly. üß† It isn‚Äôt enough to just wake up and go to your desk, fire up your brokerage and begin to trade. You need to have a plan.

Each night I post watchlist tickers for the team to review with reasoning why they make the watchlist. üìà This gives them enough time to go through the charts on every time frame and identify a few things.

Look for the overall trend and macro levels of support and resistance using the daily chart. üëÄ Look for patterns and note the previous days close using the 5minute chart. Check for recent news on the ticker.

Additionally, evaluate the current market sentiment. ‚úÖ Does it make sense to play this ticker in a market that is coming down or going up?

This goes along with not being a sheep. üêë Please don‚Äôt blindly follow others trades. Always do your own due diligence and put some time into the job. It will pay off for you in the long run.

accessibility_caption: Photo by Sheri Salargo in Kelso Dunes. Image may contain: sky, outdoor and nature
insta_description:
Isolation and uncertainty can be scary. I know that my anxiety has flared up immeasurably for a multitude a reasons. Yet, this photo I took on vacation has a strange way of soothing me. ‚Ä¢

There can be a peace in isolation, a chance to look inside and find the true self; the one that is always there even when buried by fear and doubt. It is the only constant and when we are able to silence ourselves enough, it can be found. I am attempting to turn my fears inside out, listen deeply and find the glimmers of self to get me through this unknown. ‚Ä¢

The dunes remind me that everything shifts and changes. Nothing ever looks the same a week, a day, an hour from now. These dunes don‚Äôt look the same today as they did here a couple weeks ago, yet they don‚Äôt fight it. The wind blows and shapes them anew; still beautiful all the same. ‚Ä¢

These winds we‚Äôre facing right now are fierce but they will not last forever. I am going to try to go with the flow, bend with the wind and let it shape me into someone new. May we all be better on the other side. Much love ‚ù§Ô∏è.
location.name: Kelso Dunes

accessibility_caption: Photo by winingawaytheweekend in George Hotel, Stamford. Image may contain: 1 person, sitting, drink and indoor
insta_description: Last week I went to a wine tasting with Jim ‚Äòwild boy‚Äô Clendenen in bizarrely, my local town. Jim was on a bit of a tour of the @fieldsmorrisverdin clients, which included The George of Stamford thanks to the magnificent organisation of Katie Rodway. Jim was everything I expected him to be; enthusiastic, full of stories, a little rough around the edges, a font of knowledge and passion. A bit of a rebel too, an outsider, accepted by those who happily live outside the Robert Parker realms. I think I will write a full blog up about the supper, I just haven‚Äôt had the chance to get back to my notes yet. But for now, I will just tell you about this wine, my favourite of the evening. Jim started making Hildegard in 1998, blending Pinot Gris, Pinot Blanc and Aligot√© from a plot of land that could grow seriously concentrated grapes. Well, small yields, intense flavour. They were aged separately in French oak for two years, blended and released with the name Hildegard as a nod to the Empress, the second wife of Charlemagne. This wine is just so interesting for the senses. It‚Äôs almost funky on the nose, it reminds me of popcorn a little, super sweet and nutty. But then to taste it, and the oily freshness makes you question the grapes. It just tastes like a really good Chardonnay! Super moreish, outstanding length, really very impressive. Have you tried any Au Bon Climat wines? What‚Äôs your favourite?

Yesterday we asked you in our stories if you wanted to see quarantine content or photos from our travels that could keep you wanderlusting; and you all pretty much said keep it real but keep us dreaming. With everything going on it kind of feels like the world knew we all collectively needed a break. A break from the stress of work, a break from always traveling and a break from our constant excuses. accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick in North Park, San Diego. Image may contain: food
insta_description:
I braved @costco yesterday and was hoping that my strategic choice of choosing their location next to the largest @amazon shipping hub in SoCal would prove to be wise. Unfortunately they were out of the essential items I needed. My family in four separate households refused to hoard and now we are nearly out of items that others have decided to hoard, and some, even sell at a ridiculous profit. I don't focus on this or get angry as my employment has evaporated with the @cagovernor @gavinnewsom passing AB5 and the Covid-19 pandemic. Gig Chefs like me are in an incredibly difficult position. We won't get any of the aid that's currently being worked on by our ridiculous inept government and administration. I had to spend wisely as I didn't run out and hoard like everyone else and I rely on Food Stamps to purchase my food so it's been difficult. My choices are so strange as I look for shelf stable high protein items like nuts and beans. My girlfriend had a co-worker give her a 10lb bag of Basmati Rice and that kind act nearly brought me to tears. We can share the rice and take 5lbs each back to our individual households and rest assured we will eat. As a child of generational poverty I thankfully have a skill set of knowing how to make inexpensive food stretch and how to get creative with it. These are tough and scary times indeed. All that being said the $4.99 box of croissants are an amazing luxury that honestly makes things feel almost normal. The breakfast sandwiches I was able to make this morning took away reality for just enough time to take a breath and enjoy a tasty bite of buttery croissant with fried egg, cheddar cheese and some @traderjoes Everything Bagel Seasoning. I hope I can find a job. I hope I can find a way to pay rent and that my family can find a way to pay their rent. I hope we don't run out of food and I hope we all get through this healthy and alive.
.
.

My mind goes through a rollercoaster of emotions every hour. 
But one thing is constant: this fucking sucks.
So let me be real right now. Ryan and I both work in industries that have been negatively effected. And it‚Äôs scary right now.
Last night I took my ‚Äòlast‚Äô yoga class, as we are temporarily closing until this all goes away. I cried myself to sleep the other night, I cried when I got to the studio, I cried on my mat, I cried in the arms of coworkers/friends, and I cried when clients spoke up at the end of class saying the would not be cancelling their memberships and would help with whatever we needed. 
I don‚Äôt know why this is happening. Some days I‚Äôm angry at other yogis for seemingly sweeping this under the rug, not wanting to talk or breathe life into it, and slapping a happy sticker on it. But then some days I act the same way. There‚Äôs no right or wrong way to be right now; as long as you are kind and compassionate.
The only comfort I find in this right now: is that the Earth needs this. We‚Äôve mistreated her for so long and she‚Äôs finally had enough. When I see reports of certain cities seeing blue skies for the first time in a long time, or plant regrowth, or cleaner air...that‚Äôs a positive in all of this. She‚Äôs forcing us to slow down. Come back to ourselves and reconnect with her. She‚Äôs showing us how strong and powerful she is. And we have to respect that. We‚Äôre forced to now. And that‚Äôs the only thing giving me some comfort right now. That this is part of her plan and we will all be ok, and stronger by the end of all this.
Check on your family, your friends, your neighbors. Send a text or call them. Reconnect with your loved ones and with Mother Nature. I‚Äôm grounding into this as best I can. Much love to you all üíõ .
.
.

accessibility_caption: Photo by Robert Krayer in Joshua Tree National Park with @outsidemagazine, @backpackermag, @usinterior, @rei, @nationalparklife, @joshuatreenps, @nationalparkgeek, @nationalparkobsessed, and @national_park_photographer. Image may contain: one or more people, sky, tree, mountain, outdoor and nature
insta_description:
One thing I really enjoy about the American west is the freedom, especially camping.  Getting to pick your own campsite in the wilderness instead of being confined to one site along the trail is awesome.  Last time I was in Joshua Tree, every single campsite was full and the main parts of the park were packed, but as soon as I hiked a mile or so into the desert, there was hardly anybody to be found.  So I found a site next to a beautiful joshua tree and set myself up for the evening!  Nothing like a campsite with a view! -

As a person who enjoys staying at home, this feeling came as a surprise to me. But I think I‚Äôve pinned down why. You see earlier, I had the OPTION to go out. It was a choice I made to stay in. Free will or the illusion of it and what not. But now, it‚Äôs not a option (do not @ me haters) and that‚Äôs what feels like a grip slowly tightening around my neck. 
_
I have a game plan. Since I‚Äôm working from home - that‚Äôs a definite chunk of my day spent occupied. For the rest of it - I‚Äôve made a timetable. Even scheduled time for reading and tea breaks and workouts. I took inventory of all the stuff I have in my pantry and planned meals for three days ahead. I hope sticking to a routine is going to stop me to potating (i.e acting like a potato) and actually feel like I‚Äôve done things at the end of the day. I‚Äôll let you know how it goes in three days. 
_
The internet is full of things you can do right now, by yourself. (Yes, that too.) And a little self care and introspection never hurt nobody. Enjoy this. I hope you have enough toilet paper.

insta_description:
Acting Advice: "Only in spontaneity can we be who we truly are."
‚Äî John McLaughlin

To be spontaneous is to truly be alive! When we are spontaneous, active in the moment, we can be who we truly are. And who we are is a subset of our current impulses. 
When you are spontaneous, you find yourself out of control going with the impulses that come not from the mind but from the very "now" moment you currently live in. When you are spontaneous you release a creative energy that the mind doesn't understand. The world and social conditioning tells your brain to follow the patterns of safety. When we aren't spontaneous we are allowing the logical mind to be in control. The mind is always trying to take control. When you step out, you step out of the norm and the pattern of what logically "should" happen. Understand...there is so much creative energy in each of us if only we could release it and channel it out of our body and let our soul be seen. 
In acting, you want to live in that creative spontaneous "now" moment. How do you do this? Work hard and prepare. Allow the script to get deep inside so that when the time comes you can work in that spontaneous "now" moment and act on instinct. As an actor, you seek to stay in that spontaneous now moment. You want your true self to be seen in your acting. Only then can your creativity be unleashed!

When we aren't spontaneous we are allowing the logical mind to be in control. The mind is always trying to take control. When you step out, you step out of the norm and the pattern of what logically "should" happen. Understand...there is so much creative energy in each of us if only we could release it and channel it out of our body and let our soul be seen. 
In acting, you want to live in that creative spontaneous "now" moment. How do you do this? Work hard and prepare. Allow the script to get deep inside so that when the time comes you can work in that spontaneous "now" moment and act on instinct. As an actor, you seek to stay in that spontaneous now moment. You want your true self to be seen in your acting. Only then can your creativity be unleashed!

insta_description:
My mom gave me this bracelet and it encompasses so much of what I believe in is essential to healing. She didn't give it to me on my best day, or after I published my book, she gave it to me while I was still in the throes of my illness‚Äîand those close to me didn't know if I was going to live or die.

I used to subject myself to the negative noise of those who DIDN'T believe in me and gave me their own death sentence and would feed the immense guilt and shame I already was battling. It wasn't until I cut these people out and fully embraced the support from those who loved me that I was able to start healing.

Even at my worst, people like my mom saw the best in me.

When you are struggling with severe depression, it is absolutely essential to surround yourself with people who believe in you until you can believe in yourself. Surround yourself with goodness‚òÄÔ∏è

insta_description:
üî•More Advanced Stability Ball Core Work. üß±Plank üèÉüèø‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èSprint ‚ôªÔ∏èProgressions.
These variations of plank are great for athletes to challenege their core in a safe, yet dynamic way. These movements functionally compliment the sprint cycle. They require copious amounts of tension throughout the torso, glutes, and hip flexors, just like traditional sprinting. The upper body gets fired up from stabilizing, which supports the muscles need for rapid firing during upper/lower body limb exchange during sprint gait. Lastly the deep core muscles like the transverse abdominas must stay active, as well as the oblique complex and glute complex. This movement progression is not just tough for the sake of being tough, it is tough because the body has to find balance while performing these movements. Even a high level athlete or fitness practioner may struggle with these because one side of the body is overcompensating. You will immediately know if one side is too tight, not firing up properly, or weaker than the other side.

The resistance band made these planks much tougher on my upper body and torso because the band not only acted upon my hands, but also through my center of mass. The LPHC (Lumbo Pelvic Hip Complex) a.k.a. mid section of the body have to work hard to stay stable under normal conditions when only gravity is acting upon the body. So when extra resistance is placed upon the kinetic chain, the body usually looks to compromise or bend right in the middle, just like a chain link. Unless of course, that urge to collapse is combated with proper alignment, awareness, and tension throughout the spine.

The stability ball reinforces this, by making it very difficult to maintain a flat back. To counter this sensation, hands must stay actively pressing into the ball, while at the same time lifting through the navel, and maintaining a posterior tilt in the pelvis. Otherwise what you get are rounded shoulders, and a back arch. 
This combo is simple, yet gives great feedback to the body. I was able to keep a relative straight lines while also feeling that my body could achieve even better alignment. Seeing progression, and seeing potential. #patienceJu

An order issued by the governor's office Monday night temporarily authorizes local governments to halt evictions and directs the state's Department of Business Oversight and Housing to collaborate on efforts to help Californians avoid foreclosure.

The efforts come as the state is seeking to slow the spread of the coronavirus and as public officials have faced criticism from progressive activists for not doing more to halt evictions and provide rent relief amid the outbreak, which has sickened thousands and caused thousands more to suffer lost wages due to shuttered businesses. "People shouldn't lose or be forced out of their home because of the spread of COVID-19," said Newsom. "Over the next few weeks, everyone will have to make sacrifices - but a place to live shouldn't be one of them. I strongly encourage cities and counties take up this authority to protect Californians." üè°
